To find the matrix for projecting onto the vector $\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}$, we use the projection formula:
If $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}$, then the projection formula gives us:
The projection matrix $\mathbf{P}$ is given by: 
\mathbf{P} = \frac{1}{(-3)^2 + (-2)^2} \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} -3 & -2 \end{pmatrix}
= \frac{1}{13} \begin{pmatrix} 9 & 6 \\ 6 & 4 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{align*}
We know that a projection matrix $\mathbf{P}$ satisfies the property $\mathbf{P}^2 = \mathbf{P}$.
If we square $\mathbf{P}$, we get:

  \begin{pmatrix}
-9/13 & -6/13 \\
-6/13 & -4/13 \end{pmatrix}
We know that    \begin{pmatrix}
-9/13 & \boxed{-6/13} \\
-6/13 & \boxed{-4/13}\end{pmatrix}
We now know that   P^{-1} doesn’t exist, since determinant(P) is zero and  P^{-1} is undefined and given as the zero matrix which is represented as \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} since a projection matrix cannot be the inverse of any matrix because, P^{2}=P can be only possible if: \text{rank(P)=trace(P) since: \text{rank}(P)=trace(P), which cannot happen in a square matrix greater than 1\\times 1, as if we take 2\\times 2 matrix}\]
Thus, The correct answer is.
 \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}}
This concludes our step-by-step reasoning to find $\mathbf{P}^{-1}$.

