\[ \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} \frac{2}{15} & -\frac{1}{15} & -\frac{1}{3} \\ -\frac{1}{15} & \frac{1}{30} & \frac{1}{6} \\ -\frac{1}{3} & \frac{1}{6} & \frac{5}{6} \end{pmatrix} \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1} \]
is indeed idempotent, and hence it must be a projection matrix that projects onto the line spanned by some vector $\mathbf{v}$.
The image of the projection matrix $\mathbf{P}$ onto $\mathbf{v}$ is equal to $\mathbf{v}$.
We can find $\mathbf{v}$ by taking any of the columns of the projection matrix. We will take the first column of the matrix, which is
\[\mathbf{v}= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{2}{15} \\ -\frac{1}{15} \\ -\frac{1}{3} \end{pmatrix}. \] 
This gives us the function of $\mathbf{v}$ as $\begin{pmatrix}\frac{2}{15} \\ -\frac{1}{15}\\ \frac{-1}{3}\end{pmatrix}$
, however, we are required to provide the values as integers. So $\frac{2}{15} = \frac{4}{30} = \frac{8}{60} = \frac{4}{30}$ so it can also be written as $\frac{8}{60}$ and with the same logic $\frac{-1}{15} = \frac{-2}{30}$, and $\frac{-1}{3} = \frac{-10}{30}.$
We can then multiply through by 30 to get:
$\frac{8}{60} \cdot 30 = \frac{240}{60}$,
$\frac{-2}{30} \cdot 30 = \frac{-60}{30}$, and
$\frac{-10}{30} \cdot 30 = \frac{-300}{30}$.
We get
\[ \mathbf{v}= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{240}{60} \\ \frac{-60}{30} \\ \frac{-300}{30} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ -10 \end{pmatrix}, \]
so the direction vector of the line is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ -10 \end{pmatrix}}$.

